{
  "Osteoporosis is characterized by:": "",
  "Muscle weakness only": "",
  "Excess bone growth": "",
  "Decreased bone density and increased fracture risk": "",
  "Joint inflammation only": "",
  "Osteoporosis is a metabolic bone disease in which bone resorption exceeds bone formation, resulting in reduced bone mass and density. This makes bones fragile and significantly increases the risk of fractures.": "",
  "The population most at risk for osteoporosis is:": "",
  "Teenagers": "",
  "Children": "",
  "Young men": "",
  "Postmenopausal women": "",
  "Postmenopausal women are at highest risk for osteoporosis because the dramatic decline in estrogen levels after menopause removes the protective effect estrogen has on bone, accelerating osteoclast activity and bone loss.": "",
  "Rheumatoid arthritis is:": "",
  "Caused by mechanical wear and tear": "",
  "Caused by bone fractures": "",
  "Found only in the elderly": "",
  "An autoimmune disease attacking the synovial membrane": "",
  "Rheumatoid arthritis (RA) is a chronic autoimmune disease in which the immune system mistakenly attacks the synovial membrane of joints, causing inflammation, swelling, pain, and eventual joint destruction. It can affect people of any age.": "",
  "A compound (open) fracture means:": "",
  "The broken bone has pierced through the skin": "",
  "Only a hairline crack is present": "",
  "The bone has bent without breaking completely": "",
  "The skin remains intact over the fracture": "",
  "A compound (open) fracture is one in which the broken bone has penetrated through the skin, creating an open wound. This type is particularly dangerous because the exposed bone is at high risk for infection.": "",
  "A greenstick fracture is:": "",
  "A complete break through the bone": "",
  "An incomplete break common in children where the bone bends": "",
  "A fracture caused by a twisting force": "",
  "A fracture that penetrates the skin": "",
  "A greenstick fracture is an incomplete fracture common in children, whose bones are more flexible. Like a green twig, the bone bends and cracks on one side but does not break completely through.": "",
  "Osteogenesis imperfecta is caused by:": "",
  "Bacterial infection of bone": "",
  "Vitamin D deficiency": "",
  "Aging and wear": "",
  "A genetic defect in collagen production": "",
  "Osteogenesis imperfecta ('brittle bone disease') is a genetic disorder caused by defective type I collagen production. Since collagen provides the framework for bone mineralization, defective collagen results in extremely brittle bones that fracture easily.": "",
  "Gout is caused by:": "",
  "Trauma": "",
  "Bacterial infection": "",
  "Uric acid crystal deposits in joints": "",
  "Cartilage wear and tear": "",
  "Gout is an inflammatory arthritis caused by the deposition of monosodium urate (uric acid) crystals in joints, most commonly the big toe. It results from elevated blood uric acid levels and causes severe, sudden attacks of pain and swelling.": "",
  "DEXA scans are primarily used to diagnose:": "",
  "Muscle injuries": "",
  "Bone fractures": "",
  "Rheumatoid arthritis": "",
  "Osteoporosis by measuring bone mineral density": "",
  "Dual-energy X-ray Absorptiometry (DEXA) is the gold standard imaging test for measuring bone mineral density (BMD). It is used to diagnose osteoporosis and osteopenia and to monitor treatment effectiveness.": "",
  "Paget's disease of bone involves:": "",
  "Only muscle weakness": "",
  "Excessive and disorganized bone remodeling": "",
  "Vitamin D excess": "",
  "No bone activity at all": "",
  "Paget's disease is characterized by chaotic, excessive bone remodeling in which osteoclasts become overactive, followed by disorganized osteoblast activity. The resulting bone is structurally abnormal, enlarged, and weak despite appearing dense on X-ray.": "",
  "A herniated disc involves:": "",
  "A fracture of the vertebral body": "",
  "A joint dislocation in the spine": "",
  "A torn spinal ligament only": "",
  "The nucleus pulposus protruding through the annulus fibrosus": "",
  "A herniated (slipped) disc occurs when the gel-like nucleus pulposus of an intervertebral disc pushes through a tear in the tough outer annulus fibrosus. The protruding material can compress nearby spinal nerves, causing pain, numbness, or weakness.": "",
  "What is osteoarthritis?": "",
  "A degenerative joint disease caused by wear and tear of articular cartilage": "",
  "An autoimmune disease that attacks the synovial membrane": "",
  "An infection of the bone and joint": "",
  "A metabolic bone disease causing low bone density": "",
  "Osteoarthritis (OA) is the most common form of arthritis, caused by progressive degeneration of articular cartilage from mechanical wear and tear over time. As cartilage erodes, bones rub together, causing pain, stiffness, and loss of mobility.": "",
  "What is a pathological fracture?": "",
  "A fracture that occurs during surgical procedures": "",
  "A fracture caused by high-impact trauma in healthy bone": "",
  "A fracture that occurs in bone weakened by disease, often from minimal trauma": "",
  "A fracture that fails to heal and remains permanently broken": "",
  "A pathological fracture occurs in bone that has been weakened by an underlying disease such as osteoporosis, bone cancer, or infection. These fractures can occur from minimal force or even normal daily activities that would not break healthy bone.": "",
  "What is a stress fracture?": "",
  "A fracture caused by bone disease": "",
  "A small crack in bone caused by repetitive, low-impact forces over time": "",
  "A fracture caused by a single traumatic impact": "",
  "A fracture that penetrates through the skin": "",
  "A stress fracture is a small crack in a bone that develops gradually from repetitive, submaximal forces that exceed the bone's ability to repair microdamage. They are common in runners, military recruits, and athletes who rapidly increase training intensity.": "",
  "What is a dislocation?": "",
  "An injury in which bones at a joint are forced out of their normal alignment": "",
  "A break in the continuity of a bone": "",
  "Stretching or tearing of a tendon": "",
  "Inflammation of the bursa surrounding a joint": "",
  "A dislocation (luxation) occurs when the articular surfaces of bones at a joint are completely displaced from their normal position. It typically involves stretching or tearing of the joint capsule and ligaments and requires medical reduction to realign the bones.": "",
  "What is scoliosis?": "",
  "An abnormal lateral curvature of the spine": "",
  "A normal developmental curvature of the spine": "",
  "An excessive anterior curvature of the lumbar spine": "",
  "An excessive posterior curvature of the thoracic spine": "",
  "Scoliosis is an abnormal lateral (side-to-side) curvature of the spine, typically presenting as a C-shaped or S-shaped deviation. Most cases are idiopathic (unknown cause) and are typically diagnosed during adolescence.": "",
  "What is kyphosis?": "",
  "An excessive inward lumbar curve": "",
  "A fracture of multiple vertebrae": "",
  "An excessive posterior curvature of the thoracic spine, commonly called hunchback": "",
  "Kyphosis is an exaggerated posterior convexity of the thoracic spine, producing a rounded upper back or 'hunchback' appearance. It can result from poor posture, osteoporotic vertebral compression fractures, or degenerative disc disease.": "",
  "What is lordosis?": "",
  "An excessive posterior curvature of the upper back": "",
  "An excessive anterior curvature of the lumbar spine, commonly called swayback": "",
  "Compression of vertebral bodies": "",
  "A lateral curvature of the spine": "",
  "Lordosis is an exaggerated inward (anterior) curvature of the lumbar spine, often called swayback. Contributing factors include obesity, pregnancy, poor posture, and weak abdominal muscles that fail to adequately support the lower spine.": "",
  "What does osteomyelitis mean?": "",
  "Softening of bones due to vitamin deficiency": "",
  "Excessive bone remodeling": "",
  "A benign tumor of bone tissue": "",
  "An infection of the bone and bone marrow, usually caused by bacteria": "",
  "Osteomyelitis is an infection of bone and bone marrow, most commonly caused by Staphylococcus aureus bacteria. It can reach bone through the bloodstream, direct contamination from an open fracture, or spread from an adjacent soft tissue infection.": "",
  "What does the term comminuted fracture mean?": "",
  "A fracture where the skin is pierced by the bone": "",
  "A fracture along the length of the bone": "",
  "A fracture where the bone bends without breaking completely": "",
  "A fracture in which the bone is shattered into three or more fragments": "",
  "A comminuted fracture is one in which the bone is broken into three or more pieces (fragments). These fractures typically result from high-energy trauma and are more difficult to treat because the multiple fragments must be realigned and stabilized.": "",
  "What are bisphosphonates?": "",
  "Medications that inhibit osteoclast activity, used to treat osteoporosis": "",
  "Antibiotics used to treat bone infections": "",
  "Hormones that stimulate bone growth in children": "",
  "Minerals that strengthen bone directly": "",
  "Bisphosphonates (such as alendronate and risedronate) are a class of medications that slow bone loss by inhibiting osteoclast activity. They are widely used as first-line treatment for osteoporosis to reduce fracture risk.": "",
  "A 72-year-old woman stumbles on a curb and falls onto her hip. X-rays reveal a fracture of the femoral neck even though the fall seemed minor. Her physician explains that the fracture occurred because her bones were already weakened. What type of fracture is this?": "",
  "A stress fracture from repetitive activity": "",
  "A pathological fracture due to osteoporosis": "",
  "A greenstick fracture": "",
  "A compound (open) fracture": "",
  "This is a pathological fracture because the bone was already weakened by osteoporosis before the fall occurred. Minimal trauma that would not fracture healthy bone can cause breaks in osteoporotic bone, especially at the femoral neck, vertebrae, and distal radius.": "",
  "A 45-year-old woman reports symmetric swelling, warmth, and morning stiffness in the small joints of both hands. Blood tests reveal elevated rheumatoid factor and anti-CCP antibodies. What is the most likely diagnosis, and what is the underlying mechanism?": "",
  "Rheumatoid arthritis, an autoimmune disease in which the immune system attacks the synovial membrane": "",
  "Osteoarthritis caused by mechanical wear of the cartilage": "",
  "Osteoporosis causing bone pain in the hands": "",
  "Gout caused by uric acid crystal deposition": "",
  "The symmetric joint involvement, morning stiffness, and positive autoimmune markers (rheumatoid factor and anti-CCP) are classic for rheumatoid arthritis. RA is an autoimmune disease in which the immune system attacks the synovial membrane, causing chronic inflammation and progressive joint destruction.": "",
  "A marathon runner develops gradually worsening pain in her right shin over several weeks of increasing training mileage. Imaging reveals a small crack in the tibia without any history of acute trauma. What is the most likely diagnosis?": "",
  "Osteomyelitis": "",
  "A compound fracture": "",
  "A stress fracture": "",
  "Paget's disease": "",
  "A stress fracture develops from repetitive, submaximal mechanical loading that overwhelms the bone's ability to repair microdamage. The gradual onset of pain during increased training, without a single traumatic event, is the hallmark presentation of a stress fracture.": "",
  "A patient with a known history of heavy alcohol use and a diet rich in red meat and shellfish wakes up at night with excruciating pain, redness, and swelling in his big toe. His physician diagnoses gout. What is the underlying cause of this patient's joint inflammation?": "",
  "Autoimmune destruction of the synovial membrane": "",
  "Degeneration of articular cartilage from overuse": "",
  "Bacterial infection from contaminated food": "",
  "Deposition of monosodium urate (uric acid) crystals in the joint, triggering an intense inflammatory response": "",
  "Gout is caused by hyperuricemia (elevated blood uric acid) leading to the deposition of monosodium urate crystals in joints. These sharp crystals trigger an intense inflammatory response, causing severe pain and swelling, most commonly in the first metatarsophalangeal joint (big toe).": "",
  "A child is brought to the hospital after multiple fractures from seemingly minor falls. The child also has blue-tinged sclera (whites of the eyes). Genetic testing confirms a collagen synthesis defect. What condition does this child most likely have?": "",
  "Rickets": "",
  "Osteogenesis imperfecta": "",
  "Osteoporosis": "",
  "Osteogenesis imperfecta (OI) is a genetic disorder causing defective type I collagen production, resulting in extremely brittle bones that fracture easily. Blue sclera is a classic associated finding because the thin, collagen-deficient sclera allows the underlying blood vessels to show through.": "",
  "A 55-year-old man presents with lower back pain radiating down his left leg. MRI shows that the nucleus pulposus of an intervertebral disc has herniated posterolaterally and is compressing the L5 nerve root. Why does a herniated disc cause leg pain?": "",
  "The herniated material fractures the vertebral body": "",
  "The protruding nucleus pulposus compresses the spinal nerve root, causing pain, numbness, or weakness in the area the nerve supplies": "",
  "The disc material enters the bloodstream and causes inflammation in the leg": "",
  "The annulus fibrosus tears the surrounding ligaments": "",
  "When the nucleus pulposus herniates through the annulus fibrosus, it can compress adjacent spinal nerve roots. Since these nerves travel to specific body regions, compression causes radiating pain, numbness, or weakness along the nerve's distribution, commonly down the leg (sciatica).": "",
  "A 10-year-old boy falls from a tree and presents with a forearm that is bent but the X-ray shows the bone is only cracked on one side. The emergency physician calls it a specific type of fracture common in children. What type of fracture is this?": "",
  "A spiral fracture": "",
  "A comminuted fracture": "",
  "A greenstick fracture is an incomplete break that occurs almost exclusively in children because their bones contain more collagen and are more flexible than adult bones. Like a green twig, the bone bends and cracks on the tension side but does not break completely.": "",
  "A patient with an open (compound) tibial fracture arrives at the emergency department. The orthopedic surgeon is especially concerned about a complication that is not a risk with closed fractures. What complication is the surgeon most worried about?": "",
  "Bone infection (osteomyelitis) because the wound exposes the bone to bacteria": "",
  "Premature growth plate closure": "",
  "Excessive callus formation": "",
  "Delayed healing from poor blood supply": "",
  "In an open (compound) fracture, the bone penetrates through the skin, creating a direct pathway for bacteria to enter the wound and reach the bone. This dramatically increases the risk of osteomyelitis (bone infection), which is why aggressive wound cleaning and antibiotics are critical.": "",
  "A physical education teacher screens adolescent students for spinal abnormalities. She asks each student to bend forward and checks for a rib hump or asymmetric trunk contour. What condition is she screening for, and why is early detection important?": "",
  "Scoliosis; early detection allows for bracing or intervention before the curvature worsens during the growth spurt": "",
  "Osteoporosis; early detection prevents future fractures": "",
  "Kyphosis; early detection prevents rib fractures": "",
  "Lordosis; early detection prevents lower back pain": "",
  "The forward bend (Adams) test screens for scoliosis by revealing trunk asymmetry or a rib hump caused by vertebral rotation. Early detection during adolescence is critical because intervention (such as bracing) can prevent the curvature from worsening during the growth spurt.": "",
  "An elderly man is found to have thickened, deformed bones in his skull and pelvis on X-ray, with markedly elevated serum alkaline phosphatase levels. His physician diagnoses him with a disorder of excessive, disorganized bone remodeling. What is this condition?": "",
  "Paget's disease of bone": "",
  "Paget's disease of bone is characterized by chaotic, excessive bone remodeling, producing thickened, enlarged, but structurally weak bone. Elevated alkaline phosphatase reflects the intense osteoblast activity. It most commonly affects the pelvis, skull, spine, and long bones of the legs.": ""
}